SQS is free for the first million requests per month, so no issue there. https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSSimpleQueueService/latest/SQSDeveloperGuide/welcome.html#sqs-pricing

Why use a cron job rather than an event listening daemon similar to Figgy's CloudFixity::Worker?

https://github.com/pulibrary/figgy/blob/40ba9ea10f26693ec887c43a4b8b1905c4b1a5bc/app/services/cloud_fixity.rb
Thanks for mentioning this. It looks like that start from a rake task -- it would die if the box was rebooted? I wanted something that would be resilient to down time.
There's a systemd service file for it like we do for sidekiq workers, it spins back up if it dies.

https://github.com/pulibrary/princeton_ansible/blob/main/roles/pulibrary.figgy_pubsub_worker/templates/pubsub.service

Okay great this way seems better then since it can be evented in a true pub / sub way.

The job has a "profile id" of `1395961370006421` but that doesn't appear to be included in the webhook message. The only way to identify these jobs is by the profile name ("FTP Dump") prepended by the job type ("Publishing Platform Job").
